00:42.040 --> 00:51.260
This is Bill Vernon and Daryl Lane. In 1982, science fiction lost one of its
most brilliant, innovative, and original writers, Philip K. Dick, dead at 53 of

00:51.260 --> 00:59.180
a stroke. Dick left us just as he was finally being discovered by a large number
of readers, both science fiction fans and non-fans. Dick had struggled since the

00:59.180 --> 01:07.840
early 1950s to write science fiction full-time, and he produced an immense
number of novels and stories, including the 1963 Hugo-winning novel The Man in

01:07.840 --> 01:15.520
the High Castle. However, for a long time, his fans were a relatively small
number of loyal followers. Right. For years, Dick's writing just never really

01:15.520 --> 01:22.040
caught on with the majority of science fiction fans. This was especially true in
the 50s and early 60s, when fans were more interested in hardware science

01:22.040 --> 01:29.460
fiction. But with the social changes of the late 60s and the advent of the new
wave, Dick's writing achieved a more deserving status. We talked with a friend

01:29.460 --> 01:36.280
of Dick's, Paul Williams, who was known in science fiction for his perceptive
portrait of Dick in an article in Rolling Stone. Others will remember Williams

01:36.280 --> 01:44.040
as a rock journalist and as the founder of Crawdaddy Magazine. Williams met Dick
at the 1968 World Science Fiction Convention in Oakland. They became friends

01:44.040 --> 01:52.020
immediately. Williams graciously consented to talking about Dick with us. During
most of his writing career, Dick made very little money. We asked Williams why

01:52.020 --> 02:05.200
Dick stuck to writing in the face of poor economic returns. I think a real
commitment, first of all, to the ultimate, I don't know if I want to say

02:05.200 --> 02:16.180
seriousness, but that's really it, a real commitment to what he was creating and
what he wanted to say, that always when he's written it's been because he had to

02:16.180 --> 02:25.620
write. And it was equally true that it became the only way he could make a
living. You know, it's a classic freelance writer situation where even though

02:25.620 --> 02:36.200
you're, you know, okay, if you only get $1,500 for a science fiction novel, then
what you have to do to stay alive is write six of them in a year, which he came

02:36.200 --> 02:39.560
pretty close to doing at one point.

02:55.920 --> 03:08.540
But Dick didn't stick strictly to writing science fiction. He wrote mainstream
novels as well. It was not until early in the 1960s that he gave up trying to

03:08.540 --> 03:19.520
become a successful mainstream writer. And even then, he didn't give up.
Although it felt like that to him at the time, he just put it away on the back

03:19.520 --> 03:29.380
burner, having tried very, very hard for 10 years. The first 10 years, while he
had his first 10 or so science fiction novels published, he wrote a mainstream

03:29.380 --> 03:40.220
novel for every science fiction novel he wrote. So really, he was writing two
novels for $1,000 advance, one of which would be published in an A-double novel,

03:40.240 --> 03:50.400
and the other of which would go from publisher to publisher and just be turned
down. And there are still 10 or 11 of those unpublished novels. So there are in

03:50.400 --> 03:57.860
existence several manuscripts of mainstream novels written by Dick. We asked
Williams if there is any chance these will ever be published. I think that it's

03:57.860 --> 03:58.640
inevitable.

04:01.280 --> 04:16.380
Bill had mixed opinions about their quality, and I haven't read most of them.
But it seems clear, although we may be surprised, that there's nothing as

04:16.380 --> 04:22.360
polished or as good as Confessions of the Craft Artist, which I think is
actually one of his five or six best books.

04:24.940 --> 04:35.080
But because of the interest of Bill's work, it seems inevitable at this point,
that one way or another, they will most or probably all be published within the

04:35.080 --> 04:49.700
next 10 or 20 years. But probably still by small publishers, not by New York
publishers. More about Philip K. Dick with Paul Williams on our next show.

