06:30.340 --> 06:37.940
This is Daryl Lane and Bill Vernon. The late Philip K. Dick published some 35
science fiction novels and a few mainstream ones as well. Among Dick's well

06:37.940 --> 06:45.920
-known science fiction novels are the Hugo Award winning The Man in the High
Castle, Martian Timeslip, The Three Stigmata of Palmer Eldritch, The Androids

06:45.920 --> 06:53.340
Dream of Electric Sheep, and Ubik. Dick's career abruptly ended after the
publication of three novels very different from all the others, Ballas, The

06:53.340 --> 07:00.320
Divine Invasion, and The Transmigration of Timothy Archer. The last one is not
science fiction. As Paul Williams told us in our last show, Dick wrote a number

07:00.320 --> 07:06.980
of mainstream novels which have yet to be published. Dick's science fiction
novels and stories are generally plotted around the character's perceptions of

07:06.980 --> 07:13.780
reality. We wondered if Dick were categorized as a science fiction writer simply
because there was no other convenient pigeonhole in which to place him. Williams

07:13.780 --> 07:28.520
said no. Well, he was truly a science fiction writer and I think that the
primary meaning of that is that you belong to the club and you learn by reading

07:28.520 --> 07:40.120
science fiction. And he came up writing stories for all the science fiction
magazines and then he started writing novels for Don Walheim at A's and was read

07:40.120 --> 07:51.760
only by science fiction readers. And was certainly aware of, you know, as a fan,
as a reader, all the science fictional plotting devices and the whole, you know,

07:52.280 --> 08:05.460
concept of the genre, the sense of, you know, those of us who read science
fiction. And I think that's what it means to be a science fiction writer in a

08:05.460 --> 08:20.320
lot of ways is to come up from that world and to stay within that world to
whatever degree, at least with part of your work. And he definitely did that. He

08:20.320 --> 08:33.720
wasn't necessarily satisfied with that. That's easy to understand. But he did,
although he was not a great reader of it, after adolescence or whatever, he

08:33.720 --> 08:44.240
really loved science fiction. And the people that he wrote for and the people
that he communicated with were all pretty much in that world. At least, yeah, I

08:44.240 --> 08:53.420
think it diversified more in the last 10 years. But still, I would consider him
very squarely a science fiction writer. Williams also told us how Dick felt

08:53.420 --> 09:06.460
about his own work. He always had a very kind of self-deprecating or humble
attitude towards his work, while at the same time always giving you to know

09:06.460 --> 09:17.800
somehow that he really took it as seriously and respected it as much as his most
ardent fans. What I'm saying is that he really knew how good it was.

09:20.880 --> 09:24.320
But he was able to be very humble about it.

09:38.020 --> 09:47.920
The apathetic response of publishers to Dick's experimental mainstream efforts
bothered him. What frustrated him, and he was very frustrated by it, was

09:47.920 --> 09:59.400
primarily that he didn't have the freedom to write what he called experimental
mainstream novels as well. And of course, it was a tremendous victory for him,

09:59.900 --> 10:10.640
finally, posthumously, but he was aware of it before he died, when the
transmigration of Timothy Archer was published in hardcover to the first

10:10.640 --> 10:14.300
publisher that he submitted it to after writing the novel and so forth.

10:17.780 --> 10:29.960
Or actually, before writing the novel. So, it was something that he always
wanted to do, to write this kind of book. The ghettoization of him, as a science

10:29.960 --> 10:37.780
fiction writer, kept in front of us for a long time. More with Paul Williams on
his friend Philip K. Dick on our next show.

