12:15.040 --> 12:22.000
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Today we're going to look at two of science
fiction author Philip K. Dick's best novels, with the help of Paul Williams, who

12:22.000 --> 12:28.960
was a close friend of Dick's. The Three Stigmata of Palmer Eldritch and The Man
in the High Castle both appeared in the early 60s. It is interesting to note

12:28.960 --> 12:36.440
that both made their first appearances in hardcover. That's significant because
most of Dick's works first appeared in paperback, 22 novels in fact. It is for

12:36.440 --> 12:44.240
this reason that the newly instituted Philip K. Dick Memorial Award honors the
year's most original science fiction paperback. The Three Stigmata of Palmer

12:44.240 --> 12:51.660
Eldritch details a future in which human colonists on Mars routinely use
powerful hallucinogens to relieve the dreariness of their plight, hard work, and

12:51.660 --> 12:59.420
loneliness. Then the mysterious Palmer Eldritch appears with a new drug so
powerful that its hallucinations totally overcome reality. Many of the passages

12:59.420 --> 13:06.560
in the book describe hallucinations and illusions so realistically that the
reader might assume Dick had had first that experience. We asked Williams if it

13:06.560 --> 13:12.880
is true that Dick had never used hallucinogens before he wrote The Three
Stigmata of Palmer Eldritch. We also asked him to comment on the report that in

13:12.880 --> 13:22.140
the aftermath of his experiments with psychedelics, Dick was afraid to read the
proofs of The Three Stigmata of Palmer Eldritch. It's true that he had never

13:22.140 --> 13:35.860
taken LSD or I think any psychedelic drugs before he wrote The Three Stigmata of
Palmer Eldritch. He had had experience with amphetamines.

13:38.940 --> 13:52.800
And as for then taking LSD and reading The Gallies, that's possibly true, except
that it was years before he read The Gallies and maybe years before he took the

13:52.800 --> 14:03.560
trip also. But he was afraid of it before he read them. He was, he always
claimed anyway, too scared to read The Gallies when they sent them to him. And

14:03.560 --> 14:11.160
he didn't finally reread the novel again, according to what he always claimed,
until a number of years later.

14:14.520 --> 14:25.480
But I'm sure there's no question that it scared him. It scared him while he
wrote it. And at one point he told an interviewer that he wrote it to kind of

14:25.480 --> 14:37.380
exercise a terrifying vision of the man with the stigmata that he was seeing in
the sky while driving to the shack on the California coast that he was doing his

14:37.380 --> 14:48.740
writing in. And so again, it was very real to him and terrifying while he was
writing in as well as a while reading it. I think, by the way, that it's a

14:48.740 --> 14:49.420
brilliant novel.

14:59.920 --> 15:05.740
The Man in the High Castle The Man in the High Castle is presently considered to
be Dick's major accomplishment. It's an alternate world novel which describes

15:05.740 --> 15:12.820
the United States in the aftermath of the Axis powers winning World War II. A
sidelight is that characters in the book learn that in an alternate world, the

15:12.820 --> 15:20.620
Allies have won. They learn this through the I Ching, the Chinese Book of
Changes. It has been reported that for a period, Dick himself consulted the I

15:20.620 --> 15:30.440
Ching, but that he repudiated it. We asked Williams if this is true. He did, in
several interviews, and he stopped using it. Since I originally was introduced

15:30.440 --> 15:42.300
to the I Ching by Phil's book and by someone else who had learned about it from
Phil's book, and still use the I Ching, I never took Phil's repudiation very

15:42.300 --> 15:49.980
seriously. But he did have the experience that many people have that the

15:49.980 --> 16:01.980
book, the oracle eventually told him, you know, to stop. That it wasn't useful
for him to keep asking questions of it. And his feeling and what he said was

16:01.980 --> 16:14.800
that, you know, it was actually trying to steer him in some wrong fashion. But I
think that that kind of incidental effect of the man in the high castle of

16:14.800 --> 16:25.800
introducing the Chinese Book of Changes to so many people who then introduced it
to the whole culture is very fascinating. We'll talk about Philip K. Dick's last

16:25.800 --> 16:27.100
three novels on our next show.

