18:00.100 --> 18:07.480
This is Daryl Lane. And Bill Vernon. Science fiction author Philip K. Dick
produced a large body of novels and short stories during the nearly 30-year span

18:07.480 --> 18:15.600
he wrote. Most of Dick's novels dealt with perceptions of reality, that is,
questions such as, what is real? Is that person real or is it a robot? Is this

18:15.600 --> 18:23.460
all an illusion? However, the last four novels Dick produced were quite
different from his previous efforts. A Scanner Darkly came out in 1977. It's

18:23.460 --> 18:31.060
Dick's tribute to all his friends who died from the effects of drugs, and it's a
warning to those contemplating their use. Dick's last three novels, Valus, The

18:31.060 --> 18:37.720
Divine Invasion, and The Transmigration of Timothy Archer, are related
thematically. They all have spiritual, mystical, religious overtones. We

18:37.720 --> 18:45.280
wondered if Dick wrote these three novels after undergoing some kind of change
of life experience. Here Paul Williams, Dick's friend for many years, comments.

18:46.540 --> 18:56.980
It's certainly something new. I mean, he, in fact, saw these three books, these
last three books, as a kind of a trilogy, even though they have different

18:56.980 --> 19:08.760
settings and subjects. The thematic material is extremely related. And it comes
out of his own personal experiences and one sort of mystical experience in

19:08.760 --> 19:24.940
particular, and also out of at least six years of really intensive research into
theology and philosophy and, in many ways, you know, the spiritual history of

19:24.940 --> 19:36.080
human beings, at least over the last 5,000 years or so, which he just totally
immersed himself in, originally on the pretext that he was doing research for

19:36.080 --> 19:44.900
Valus, which ultimately turned out to be true. But, and there was a period of
about three or four years where he didn't write a novel, and we all wondered if,

19:45.120 --> 19:57.880
you know, if he would again. And I'm sure he wondered. So that this
extraordinary work, particularly the last three books, definitely, as you say,

19:57.900 --> 20:08.540
comes from a change of life, so they're not in the sense of, you know, going
down to the church and getting religion. Williams then goes on to tell us about

20:08.540 --> 20:23.300
the experience, a revelation which awakened it. There was an awakening in him
of, brought about as exactly as he describes in Valus, by an incident, I guess,

20:23.480 --> 20:25.860
in 1975.

20:29.780 --> 20:48.640
where he's sitting in his car in a very Southern California town, Santa Ana, or
Fullerton, around there, and is kind of zapped by this pink phosphine light. And

20:48.640 --> 21:01.480
nothing was really the same again after that, but, I mean, he spent a couple of
hours in a, really, a very subtle kind of other world. And it was only his sense

21:01.480 --> 21:11.360
of the importance of this experience that really gives it its way. In other
words, exactly what he went through, somebody else might have shrugged off who

21:11.360 --> 21:22.980
didn't have his particular powers of perception and interest. That experience is
described in Valus, and in slightly different terms in the profile of Dick and

21:22.980 --> 21:31.700
Charles Platt's Dream Makers. We asked Williams about the objective reality of
Dick's experience. It's a totally subjective experience, you know, even as he

21:31.700 --> 21:40.660
describes it, right? It's something that happened to him. That, you know, in
fact, one of the issues that comes up for him is how do you prove something like

21:40.660 --> 21:57.680
that, you know, to yourself, as much as anyone else. But absolutely no question
that it was very real to him, and that, you know, the horse lover fat character

21:57.680 --> 22:08.300
in Valus is as real a self-portrait as you could find. So Dick's last three
novels, definitely a departure from his previous work, were the result of Dick's

22:08.300 --> 22:12.540
own personal experiences. On our next show, we'll take another look at this
group of novels.

