23:47.900 --> 23:55.720
This is Bill Vernon. And Daryl Lane. Fans of science fiction author Philip K.
Dick realized that Dick's last three novels, Valus, The Divine Invasion, and The

23:55.720 --> 24:03.140
Transmigration of Timothy Archer, represent a significant departure from his
earlier work. As we discussed with Dick's friend Paul Williams on our last show,

24:03.340 --> 24:11.100
these novels have a spiritual element which was brought about by a vision Dick
experienced in 1975. Only time will tell, but some feel that these three novels,

24:11.280 --> 24:18.380
especially The Transmigration of Timothy Archer, will eclipse The Man in the
High Castle as Dick's most important work. Valus is Dick's somewhat

24:18.380 --> 24:26.640
autobiographical sketch of horse lover fat, and in it are the details of Dick's
life-changing spiritual encounter. The Divine Invasion, the most overtly science

24:26.640 --> 24:33.780
fictional of the three, is a mystical treatment of the salvation of Earth in the
approaching Armageddon. The Transmigration of Timothy Archer is not science

24:33.780 --> 24:40.720
fiction. Rather, it's an experimental mainstream novel similar to those Dick
tried for years to publish. It's based quite closely on the life of the late

24:40.720 --> 24:54.400
Bishop Pike, whom Dick knew for some years. Here Paul Williams tells us a bit of
what Dick was driving at in his final three novels. He became obsessed with the

24:54.400 --> 25:06.560
revelations that he had around, and his questions about what was that happened
to him and why. And ultimately, his answers, which in effect are his answers,

25:06.860 --> 25:18.420
and in a sense it's a culmination of his entire work, his answers to tentative
or whatever, to all the questions he'd been asking in all his books. What is

25:18.420 --> 25:32.340
reality? What is history? What's really going on and why? And what is the real
nature of the forces here? And as somebody quoted Einstein as saying, you know,

25:32.380 --> 25:41.360
Einstein was asked if he could, a reporter asked him, what would you say if you
could have the answer to any question? You know, what question would you ask?

25:41.700 --> 25:44.460
And Einstein immediately answered, is the universe friendly?

25:47.740 --> 25:59.380
And that was certainly a burning question on the mind of Philip K. Dick in every
book he ever wrote. And there is a kind of extraordinary revelation in the last

25:59.380 --> 26:12.340
two or three books, in which, while still giving that incredibly penetrating,
ruthless vision of the way things really are, and often in still quite a

26:12.340 --> 26:27.940
depressing tone, he nevertheless comes through with a very strong conviction
that yes, we are ultimately in the hands of, or at least strongly under the

26:27.940 --> 26:44.400
influence of, a basically friendly preacher much greater than us that is on our
side in a battle that is far from decided. We asked Williams if some of Dick's

26:44.400 --> 26:51.840
conclusions might have been based on the tenets of any organized religion. You
could make this as similar to the Christian myth, or the myth of almost any

26:51.840 --> 27:02.360
other, you know, great world religion, or as different from it as you want it
to. You know, you could make a great case that, hey, this man believed, you

27:02.360 --> 27:11.580
know, the straight party line, or you could make a great case that he was a
heretic whose books should be burned, you know, by every organized and

27:11.580 --> 27:25.580
disorganized religion in the world, so that there's no easy conclusion as to,
because it is so uniquely his vision, as to what the meaning of the vision and

27:25.580 --> 27:35.740
the information part in his last work is. But there seems no question that he
begins

27:35.740 --> 27:49.960
to really make some very strong statements about what he finally thinks is going
on. Philip K. Dick will be sorely missed. He had his ardent fans, and his last

27:49.960 --> 27:55.880
three novels will continue to gain him new fans from outside science fiction. We
can always hope they'll go back and read his early works.

